 Law -- t14. The Unfinished Revolution: The Right to Have Rights and Birthright Citizenship -- t15. Genocide and Jurisgenesis -- t16. Jurisgenerativity in the Age of Big Data -- tPart V Deprovincializing Critical Theory -- t17. Pachamama’s Rights, Climate Crisis, and the Decolonial Cosmos -- t18. What Is the Other in Seyla Benhabib’s Another Cosmopolitanism? -- t19. Border Deaths as Forced Disappearances: Frantz Fanon and the Outlines of a Critical Phenomenology -- t20. Gender Trouble: Manhood, Inclusion, and Justice in the Political Philosophy of Martin Luther King, Jr. -- tPart VI Philosophy and Friendship -- t21. Fragments of an Intellectual Autobiography -- t22. Swimming -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeyla Benhabib’s ongoing work has expanded the range and scope of critical theory beyond its origins to address questions of gender, migration, and difference. This book brings together an ensemble of leading theorists and younger voices to explore new dimensions of Benhabib’s thought across critical theory, feminism, and democratic theory, foregrounding the intricate relationship between critique and universality.Another Universalism provides both a wide-ranging and comprehensive engagement with Benhabib’s path-breaking interventions and a panoramic tour of the cutting edge of critical theory today. Contributors take part in key debates about the field’s past and future, tackling subjects such as the relationship between democracy and cosmopolitanism, the role of law in emancipatory struggles, human domination of nature, the deprovincialization of critical theory concerning questions of race and empire, as well as Hannah Arendt’s continuing significance. Covering a wide range of debates and themes, Another Universalism is united by a core question: How can universal norms of human freedom, equality, and dignity be reconciled with particular contexts, especially ones of exclusion, difference, and adversity? Searching for universalisms that emerge from the concrete struggles of emancipatory movements, this book points toward an expansive, inclusive, and radical democratic vision.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical theory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBasdas, Umur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenhabib, Seyla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernal, Angélica María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakravarti, Sonali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornell, Drucilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDege, Carmen Lea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemiryol, Gaye İlhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEich, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmcke, Carolin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForst, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGündoğdu, Ayten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarcourt, Bernard E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJurkevics, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJurkevics, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLafont, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinden-Retek, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongo, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarkell, Patchen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca